    </p>
    <p>&nbsp;</p>
  </div><br />&nbsp;Early influences.&nbsp; The interview starts with Nirenberg giving his recollections of his school years.&nbsp; He remembers going down into some limestone caves in Florida at the age of 13-14.&nbsp; It was full of&nbsp; fossilized large animal bones.&nbsp; In fact, saber-toothed tigers were found.&nbsp; During his undergraduate degree at the University of Florida, Gainsville he got a job as a technician working on samples and calculations and working with bio-chemists.&nbsp; This led to Nirenberg doing a PhD at the University of Michigan, Ann Arbor with Jim Hogg working on sugar transport and reactions.&nbsp; He thought that University was wonderful - the freedom and the chance to learn and nobody to tell him to go to bed!<br /><br />His Grandfather came from Russia at the age of 12 and got a job in a shirt factory sweeping the floors and ended up running the factory!&nbsp; His father also worked in the shirt business for many years until he sold up the factory and bought a dairy farm.<br /><br />Nirenberg went on to get a postdoctoral position at NIH (National Institutes of Health, Bethesda, Maryland, 1959-1960) and to continue the work that he started at Michigan.&nbsp; A man who greatly influenced him was Gordon Tompkins.&nbsp; As a result of his influence he changed fields he says in order to explore and discover things.&nbsp; He started working on messenger RNA and protein synthesis.&nbsp; He worked by himself but had others like Tompkins close at hand to speak with.&nbsp; He says that he virtually lived in the laboratory (that was before he was married).<br /><br />Nirenberg goes on to speak in depth about his early and latter day scientific research.&nbsp; He says that to his horror he has found that he likes to compete as it focuses him!<br /><br />When asked by Kroto if he feels any responsibility towards society since being awarded the Nobel Prize? He says that yes he does.&nbsp; He thinks that the US should play an active role in curbing carbon dioxide omissions and is disappointed in his country for not doing so.&nbsp; He also agrees that the democratic process in the US has and is being distorted by the religious right throughout the duration of the Bush administration.&nbsp; He thinks that there should be a separation between the Church and the State.&nbsp; <br /><br />He is against the curb on stem cell research and thinks that government should support it.&nbsp; Recently he has studied stem cells research with a view to working in the area.<br /><br />He is a member of the board of the Committee for Concerned Scientists.<br />&nbsp;<br /><br /><span class="bold_title">Links To Other Information:</span></div>
		</div><!-- /Inner -->
	</div><!-- /LeftHandBlock -->
